# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: webauthn-fido2
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] Biometric identifiers are the distinctive, measurable characteristics used to label and describe individuals.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] Biometric identifiers are often categorized as physiological characteristics which are related to the shape of the body.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] Examples include, but are not limited to fingerprint, palm veins, face recognition, DNA, palm print, hand geometry, iris recognition, retina, odor/scent, voice and shape of ears.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] Behavioral characteristics are related to the pattern of behavior of a person, including but not limited to mouse movement, typing rhythm, gait, signature, voice, and behavioral profiling.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] Some researchers have coined the term "**Behaviometrics"** (behavioral biometrics) to describe the latter class of biometrics.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] More traditional means of access control include token-based identification systems, such as a driver's license or passport, and knowledge-based identification systems, such as a password or personal identification number.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] Since biometric identifiers are unique to individuals, they are more reliable in verifying identity than token and knowledge-based methods; however, the collection of biometric identifiers raises privacy concerns.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] Many different aspects of human physiology, chemistry or behavior can be used for biometric authentication.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] The selection of a particular biometric for use in a specific application involves a weighting of several factors.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] Jain *et al.* (1999) identified seven such factors to be used when assessing the suitability of any trait for use in biometric authentication.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] Biometric authentication is based upon biometric recognition which is an advanced method of recognizing biological and behavioral characteristics of an Individual.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] Proper biometric use is very application dependent.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] Certain biometrics will be better than others based on the required levels of convenience and security.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] No single biometric will meet all the requirements of every possible application.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] The block diagram illustrates the two basic modes of a biometric system.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] First, in verification (or authentication) mode the system performs a one-to-one comparison of a captured biometric with a specific template stored in a biometric database in order to verify the individual is the person they claim to be.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] Three steps are involved in the verification of a person.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] In the first step, reference models for all the users are generated and stored in the model database .
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] In the second step, some samples are matched with reference models to generate the genuine and impostor scores and calculate the threshold.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] This process may use a smart card, username, or ID number (e.g.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] PIN) to indicate which template should be used for comparison.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] *Positive recognition* is a common use of the verification mode, "where the aim is to prevent multiple people from using the same identity".
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] Second, in identification mode the system performs a one-to-many comparison against a biometric database in an attempt to establish the identity of an unknown individual.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] The system will succeed in identifying the individual if the comparison of the biometric sample to a template in the database falls within a previously set threshold.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] The latter function can only be achieved through biometrics since other methods of personal recognition, such as passwords, PINs, or keys, are ineffective.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] The first time an individual uses a biometric system is called *enrollment*.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] During enrollment, biometric information from an individual is captured and stored.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] In subsequent uses, biometric information is detected and compared with the information stored at the time of enrollment.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] Note that it is crucial that storage and retrieval of such systems themselves be secure if the biometric system is to be robust.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] The first block (sensor) is the interface between the real world and the system; it has to acquire all the necessary data.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] Most of the time it is an image acquisition system, but it can change according to the characteristics desired.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] The second block performs all the necessary pre-processing: it has to remove artifacts from the sensor, to enhance the input (e.g. removing background noise), to use some kind of normalization, etc.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] In the third block, necessary features are extracted.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] This step is an important step as the correct features need to be extracted in an optimal way.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] A vector of numbers or an image with particular properties is used to create a *template*.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] A template is a synthesis of the relevant characteristics extracted from the source.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] Elements of the biometric measurement that are not used in the comparison algorithm are discarded in the template to reduce the file size and to protect the identity of the enrollee.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] However, depending on the scope of the biometric system, original biometric image sources may be retained, such as the PIV-cards used in the Federal Information Processing Standard Personal Identity Verification (PIV) of Federal Employees and Contractors (FIPS 201).
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] During the enrollment phase, the template is simply stored somewhere (on a card or within a database or both).
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] During the matching phase, the obtained template is passed to a matcher that compares it with other existing templates, estimating the distance between them using any algorithm (e.g.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] The matching program will analyze the template with the input.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] This will then be output for a specified use or purpose (e.g. entrance in a restricted area), though it is a fear that the use of biometric data may face mission creep.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] Selection of biometrics in any practical application depending upon the characteristic measurements and user requirements.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] In selecting a particular biometric, factors to consider include, performance, social acceptability, ease of circumvention and/or spoofing, robustness, population coverage, size of equipment needed and identity theft deterrence.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] The selection of a biometric is based on user requirements and considers sensor and device availability, computational time and reliability, cost, sensor size, and power consumption.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] Multimodal biometric systems use multiple sensors or biometrics to overcome the limitations of unimodal biometric systems.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] For instance iris recognition systems can be compromised by aging irises and electronic fingerprint recognition can be worsened by worn-out or cut fingerprints.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] While unimodal biometric systems are limited by the integrity of their identifier, it is unlikely that several unimodal systems will suffer from identical limitations.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] Multimodal biometric systems can obtain sets of information from the same marker (i.e., multiple images of an iris, or scans of the same finger) or information from different biometrics (requiring fingerprint scans and, using voice recognition, a spoken passcode).
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] Multimodal biometric systems can fuse these unimodal systems sequentially, simultaneously, a combination thereof, or in series, which refer to sequential, parallel, hierarchical and serial integration modes, respectively.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] Fusion of the biometrics information can occur at different stages of a recognition system.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] In case of feature level fusion, the data itself or the features extracted from multiple biometrics are fused.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] Matching-score level fusion consolidates the scores generated by multiple classifiers pertaining to different modalities.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] Finally, in case of decision level fusion the final results of multiple classifiers are combined via techniques such as majority voting.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] Feature level fusion is believed to be more effective than the other levels of fusion because the feature set contains richer information about the input biometric data than the matching score or the output decision of a classifier.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] Therefore, fusion at the feature level is expected to provide better recognition results.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] Spoof attacks consist in submitting fake biometric traits to biometric systems, and are a major threat that can curtail their security.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] Multi-modal biometric systems are commonly believed to be intrinsically more robust to spoof attacks, but recent studies have shown that they can be evaded by spoofing even a single biometric trait.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] The Fingerprint Involves minutiae extraction (terminations and bifurcations) and matching techniques.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] Steps include image enhancement, binarization, ROI extraction, and minutiae thinning.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] The Face system uses class-based scatter matrices to calculate features for recognition, and the Palm Vein acts as an unbreakable cryptographic key, ensuring only the correct user can access the system.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] The cancelable Biometrics concept allows biometric traits to be altered slightly to ensure privacy and avoid theft.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] If compromised, new variations of biometric data can be issued.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] The Encryption fingerprint template is encrypted using the palm vein key via XOR operations.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] This encrypted Fingerprint is hidden within the face image using steganographic techniques.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] Enrollment and Verification for the Biometric data (Fingerprint, palm vein, face) are captured, encrypted, and embedded into a face image.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] The system extracts the biometric data and compares it with stored values for Verification.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] The system was tested with fingerprint databases, achieving 75% verification accuracy at an equal error rate of 25% and processing time approximately 50 seconds for enrollment and 22 seconds for Verification.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] High security due to palm vein encryption, effective against biometric spoofing, and the multimodal approach ensures reliability if one biometric fails.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] Potential for integration with smart cards or on-card systems, enhancing security in personal identification systems.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] The discriminating powers of all biometric technologies depend on the amount of entropy they are able to encode and use in matching.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] An early cataloguing of fingerprints dates back to 1885 when Juan Vucetich started a collection of fingerprints of criminals in Argentina.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] Josh Ellenbogen and Nitzan Lebovic argued that Biometrics originated in the identification systems of criminal activity developed by Alphonse Bertillon (1853–1914) and by Francis Galton's theory of fingerprints and physiognomy.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] Historian Keith Breckenridge note that Galton's travels in South Africa reinforced his early racial prejudices and inspired his later commitment to classifying human difference scientifically.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] According to Lebovic, Galton's work "led to the application of mathematical models to fingerprints, phrenology, and facial characteristics", as part of "absolute identification" and "a key to both inclusion and exclusion" of populations.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] Accordingly, "the biometric system is the absolute political weapon of our era" and a form of "soft control".
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] The theoretician David Lyon showed that during the past two decades biometric systems have penetrated the civilian market, and blurred the lines between governmental forms of control and private corporate control.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] Adaptive biometric systems aim to auto-update the templates or model to the intra-class variation of the operational data.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] The two-fold advantages of these systems are solving the problem of limited training data and tracking the temporal variations of the input data through adaptation.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] Recently, adaptive biometrics have received a significant attention from the research community.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] This research direction is expected to gain momentum because of their key promulgated advantages.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] First, with an adaptive biometric system, one no longer needs to collect a large number of biometric samples during the enrollment process.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] Second, it is no longer necessary to enroll again or retrain the system from scratch in order to cope with the changing environment.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] This convenience can significantly reduce the cost of maintaining a biometric system.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] Despite these advantages, there are several open issues involved with these systems.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] For mis-classification error (false acceptance) by the biometric system, cause adaptation using impostor sample.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] However, continuous research efforts are directed to resolve the open issues associated to the field of adaptive biometrics.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] In recent times, biometrics based on brain (electroencephalogram) and heart (electrocardiogram) signals have emerged.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] An example is finger vein recognition, using pattern-recognition techniques, based on images of human vascular patterns.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] The advantage of this newer technology is that it is more fraud resistant compared to conventional biometrics like fingerprints.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] However, such technology is generally more cumbersome and still has issues such as lower accuracy and poor reproducibility over time.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] On the portability side of biometric products, more and more vendors are embracing significantly miniaturized biometric authentication systems (BAS) thereby driving elaborate cost savings, especially for large-scale deployments.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] An operator signature is a biometric mode where the manner in which a person using a device or complex system is recorded as a verification template.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] One potential use for this type of biometric signature is to distinguish among remote users of telerobotic surgery systems that utilize public networks for communication.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] John Michael (Mike) McConnell, a former vice admiral in the United States Navy, a former director of U.S.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] National Intelligence, and senior vice president of Booz Allen Hamilton, promoted the development of a future capability to require biometric authentication to access certain public networks in his keynote speech at the 2009 Biometric Consortium Conference.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] A basic premise in the above proposal is that the person that has uniquely authenticated themselves using biometrics with the computer is in fact also the agent performing potentially malicious actions from that computer.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] However, if control of the computer has been subverted, for example in which the computer is part of a botnet controlled by a hacker, then knowledge of the identity of the user at the terminal does not materially improve network security or aid law enforcement activities.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] Rather than tags or tattoos, biometric techniques may be used to identify individual animals: zebra stripes, blood vessel patterns in rodent ears, muzzle prints, bat wing patterns, primate facial recognition and koala spots have all been tried.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] Biometrics have been considered also instrumental to the development of state authority (to put it in Foucauldian terms, of discipline and biopower).
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] By turning the human subject into a collection of biometric parameters, biometrics would dehumanize the person, infringe bodily integrity, and, ultimately, offend human dignity.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] In a well-known case, Italian philosopher Giorgio Agamben refused to enter the United States in protest at the United States Visitor and Immigrant Status Indicator (US-VISIT) program's requirement for visitors to be fingerprinted and photographed.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] Agamben argued that gathering of biometric data is a form of bio-political tattooing, akin to the tattooing of Jews during the Holocaust.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] According to Agamben, biometrics turn the human persona into a bare body.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] Agamben refers to the two words used by Ancient Greeks for indicating "life", *zoe*, which is the life common to animals and humans, just life; and *bios*, which is life in the human context, with meanings and purposes.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] Agamben envisages the reduction to bare bodies for the whole humanity.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] For him, a new bio-political relationship between citizens and the state is turning citizens into pure biological life (*zoe*) depriving them from their humanity (*bios*); and biometrics would herald this new world.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] The stark expansion of biometric technologies in both the public and private sector magnifies this concern.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] The increasing commodification of biometrics by the private sector adds to this danger of loss of human value.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] Indeed, corporations value the biometric characteristics more than the individuals value them.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] Other scholars have emphasized, however, that the globalized world is confronted with a huge mass of people with weak or absent civil identities.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] Most developing countries have weak and unreliable documents and the poorer people in these countries do not have even those unreliable documents.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] Without certified personal identities, there is no certainty of right, no civil liberty.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] One can claim his rights, including the right to refuse to be identified, only if he is an identifiable subject, if he has a public identity.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] In such a sense, biometrics could play a pivotal role in supporting and promoting respect for human dignity and fundamental rights.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] It is possible that data obtained during biometric enrollment may be used in ways for which the enrolled individual has not consented.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] Moreover, second generation biometrics, notably behavioral and electro-physiologic biometrics (e.g., based on electrocardiography, electroencephalography, electromyography), could be also used for emotion detection.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] Unintended application scope: The authentication process correctly identifies the subject when the subject did not wish to be identified.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] Covert identification: The subject is identified without seeking identification or authentication, i.e. a subject's face is identified in a crowd.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] In terms of recognition or identification performance for a given trait, a biometric system should not exhibit accuracy differences across demographic groups.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] Disparities in accuracy can lead to uneven error rates for populations defined by gender, race, age, or other attributes .
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] Therefore, biometric systems should be designed and evaluated to ensure demographic fairness, providing equitable performance for all users.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] When thieves cannot get access to secure properties, there is a chance that the thieves will stalk and assault the property owner to gain access.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] If the item is secured with a biometric device, the damage to the owner could be irreversible, and potentially cost more than the secured property.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] For example, in 2005, Malaysian car thieves cut off a man's finger when attempting to steal his Mercedes-Benz S-Class.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] In the context of biometric systems, presentation attacks may also be called "spoofing attacks".
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] As per the recent ISO/IEC 30107 standard, presentation attacks are defined as "presentation to the biometric capture subsystem with the goal of interfering with the operation of the biometric system".
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] These attacks can be either impersonation or obfuscation attacks.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] Impersonation attacks try to gain access by pretending to be someone else.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] Obfuscation attacks may, for example, try to evade face detection and face recognition systems.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] Several methods have been proposed to counteract presentation attacks.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] Biometrics are employed by many aid programs in times of crisis in order to prevent fraud and ensure that resources are properly available to those in need.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] Humanitarian efforts are motivated by promoting the welfare of individuals in need, however the use of biometrics as a form of surveillance humanitarianism can create conflict due to varying interests of the groups involved in the particular situation.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] Disputes over the use of biometrics between aid programs and party officials stalls the distribution of resources to people that need help the most.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] In July 2019, the United Nations World Food Program and Houthi Rebels were involved in a large dispute over the use of biometrics to ensure resources are provided to the hundreds of thousands of civilians in Yemen whose lives are threatened.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] The refusal to cooperate with the interests of the United Nations World Food Program resulted in the suspension of food aid to the Yemen population.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] The use of biometrics may provide aid programs with valuable information, however its potential solutions may not be best suited for chaotic times of crisis.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] Conflicts that are caused by deep-rooted political problems, in which the implementation of biometrics may not provide a long-term solution.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] One advantage of passwords over biometrics is that they can be re-issued.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] If a token or a password is lost or stolen, it can be cancelled and replaced by a newer version.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] This is not naturally available in biometrics.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] If someone's face is compromised from a database, they cannot cancel or reissue it.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] If the electronic biometric identifier is stolen, it is nearly impossible to change a biometric feature.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] This renders the person's biometric feature questionable for future use in authentication, such as the case with the hacking of security-clearance-related background information from the Office of Personnel Management (OPM) in the United States.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] Cancelable biometrics is a way in which to incorporate protection and the replacement features into biometrics to create a more secure system.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] "Cancelable biometrics refers to the intentional and systematically repeatable distortion of biometric features in order to protect sensitive user-specific data.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] If a cancelable feature is compromised, the distortion characteristics are changed, and the same biometrics is mapped to a new template, which is used subsequently.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] Several methods for generating new exclusive biometrics have been proposed.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] The first fingerprint-based cancelable biometric system was designed and developed by Tulyakov *et al.* Essentially, cancelable biometrics perform a distortion of the biometric image or features before matching.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] The variability in the distortion parameters provides the cancelable nature of the scheme.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] Soft biometrics are understood as **not strict biometrical** recognition practices that are proposed in favour of identity cheaters and stealers.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] Traits are physical, behavioral or adhered human characteristics that have been derived from the way human beings normally distinguish their peers (e.g. height, gender, hair color).
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] They are used to complement the identity information provided by the primary biometric identifiers.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] Although soft biometric characteristics lack the distinctiveness and permanence to recognize an individual uniquely and reliably, and can be easily faked, they provide some evidence about the users identity that could be beneficial.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] In other words, despite the fact they are unable to individualize a subject, they are effective in distinguishing between people.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] Combinations of personal attributes like gender, race, eye color, height and other visible identification marks can be used to improve the performance of traditional biometric systems.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] Most soft biometrics can be easily collected and are actually collected during enrollment.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] Two main ethical issues are raised by soft biometrics.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] Second, soft biometrics have strong potential for categorizing and profiling people, so risking of supporting processes of stigmatization and exclusion.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] Many countries, including the United States, are planning to share biometric data with other nations.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] According to an article written in 2009 by S.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] Magnuson in the National Defense Magazine entitled "Defense Department Under Pressure to Share Biometric Data" the United States has bilateral agreements with other nations aimed at sharing biometric data.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] Certain members of the civilian community are worried about how biometric data is used but full disclosure may not be forthcoming.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] This also potentially applies to Biometrics.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] It goes on to say that this is a classic feature of intelligence and military operations.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] In short, the goal is to preserve the security of 'sources and methods'.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] The frequent use of biometric authentication for security and the permanence of an individuals biometrics make the security of biometric data crucial.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] The United States does not have a nationwide data privacy law that includes biometrics.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] Several states and local governments, led by the Illinois Biometric Information Privacy Act, have legislation regarding biometric data.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] The FTC has also taken actions to protect biometric data including against Facebook in 2019, charging they misrepresented their uses of facial recognition technology.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] Among low to middle income countries, roughly 1.2 billion people have already received identification through a biometric identification program.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] There are also numerous countries applying biometrics for voter registration and similar electoral purposes.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] India's national ID program called Aadhaar is the largest biometric database in the world.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] It is a biometrics-based digital identity assigned for a person's lifetime, verifiable online instantly in the public domain, at any time, from anywhere, in a paperless way.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] It is designed to enable government agencies to deliver a retail public service, securely based on biometric data (fingerprint, iris scan and face photo), along with demographic data (name, age, gender, address, parent/spouse name, mobile phone number) of a person.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] The data is transmitted in encrypted form over the internet for authentication, aiming to free it from the limitations of physical presence of a person at a given place.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] About 550 million residents have been enrolled and assigned 480 million Aadhaar national identification numbers as of 7 November 2013.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] It aims to cover the entire population of 1.2 billion in a few years.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] However, it is being challenged by critics over privacy concerns and possible transformation of the state into a surveillance state, or into a Banana republic.§ The project was also met with mistrust regarding the safety of the social protection infrastructures.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] To tackle the fear amongst the people, India's supreme court put a new ruling into action that stated that privacy from then on was seen as a fundamental right.
[src:webauthn-fido2/biometrics] On 24 August 2017 this new law was established.
[src:webauthn-fido2/client-to-authenticator-protocol] The **Client to Authenticator Protocol** (**CTAP**) enables a roaming, user-controlled cryptographic authenticator (such as a smartphone or a hardware security key) to interoperate with a client platform such as a laptop.
[src:webauthn-fido2/client-to-authenticator-protocol] The standard is also adopted as ITU-T **Recommendation X.1278**.
[src:webauthn-fido2/client-to-authenticator-protocol] CTAP is complementary to the Web Authentication (WebAuthn) standard published by the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C).
[src:webauthn-fido2/client-to-authenticator-protocol] WebAuthn and CTAP are the primary outputs of the FIDO2 Project, a joint effort between the FIDO Alliance and the W3C.
[src:webauthn-fido2/client-to-authenticator-protocol] CTAP is based upon previous work done by the FIDO Alliance, in particular the Universal 2nd Factor (U2F) authentication standard.
[src:webauthn-fido2/client-to-authenticator-protocol] Specifically, the FIDO U2F 1.2 Proposed Standard (July 11, 2017) became the starting point for the CTAP Proposed Standard, the latest version 2.2 of which was published on February 28, 2025.
[src:webauthn-fido2/client-to-authenticator-protocol] The CTAP specification refers to two protocol versions, the **CTAP1**/U2F protocol and the **CTAP2** protocol.
[src:webauthn-fido2/client-to-authenticator-protocol] An authenticator that implements CTAP2 is called a FIDO2 authenticator (also called a WebAuthn authenticator).
[src:webauthn-fido2/client-to-authenticator-protocol] If that authenticator implements CTAP1/U2F as well, it is backward compatible with U2F.
[src:webauthn-fido2/client-to-authenticator-protocol] The protocol uses the CBOR binary data serialization format.
[src:webauthn-fido2/fido-alliance] The **FIDO** (**Fast IDentity Online**) **Alliance** is an open industry association launched in February 2013 whose stated mission is to develop and promote authentication standards that "help reduce the world’s over-reliance on passwords".
[src:webauthn-fido2/fido-alliance] FIDO addresses the lack of interoperability among devices that use strong authentication and reduces the problems users face creating and remembering multiple usernames and passwords.
[src:webauthn-fido2/fido-alliance] The USB security token device may be used to authenticate using a simple password (e.g. four-digit PIN) or by pressing a button.
[src:webauthn-fido2/fido-alliance] The specifications emphasize a device-centric model.
[src:webauthn-fido2/fido-alliance] Authentication over an insecure channel happens using public-key cryptography.
[src:webauthn-fido2/fido-alliance] The user's device registers the user to a server by registering a public key.
[src:webauthn-fido2/fido-alliance] To authenticate the user, the device signs a challenge from the server using the private key that it holds.
[src:webauthn-fido2/fido-alliance] The keys on the device are unlocked by a local user gesture such as a biometric or pressing a button.
[src:webauthn-fido2/fido-alliance] FIDO provides two types of user experiences depending on which protocol is used.
[src:webauthn-fido2/fido-alliance] Both protocols define a common interface at the client for whatever local authentication method the user exercises.
[src:webauthn-fido2/fido-alliance] The following open specifications may be obtained from the FIDO web site.
[src:webauthn-fido2/fido-alliance] The U2F 1.0 Proposed Standard (October 9, 2014) was the starting point for the specification known as FIDO 2.0 Proposed Standard (September 4, 2015).
[src:webauthn-fido2/fido-alliance] The latter was formally submitted to the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C) on November 12, 2015.
[src:webauthn-fido2/fido-alliance] Subsequently, the first Working Draft of the W3C Web Authentication (WebAuthn) standard was published on May 31, 2016.
[src:webauthn-fido2/fido-alliance] The WebAuthn standard has been revised numerous times since then, becoming a W3C Recommendation on March 4, 2019.
[src:webauthn-fido2/fido-alliance] Meanwhile the U2F 1.2 Proposed Standard (July 11, 2017) became the starting point for the Client to Authenticator Protocol 2.0 Proposed Standard, which was published on September 27, 2017.
[src:webauthn-fido2/fido-alliance] FIDO CTAP 2.0 complements W3C WebAuthn, both of which are in scope for the *FIDO2 Project*.
[src:webauthn-fido2/fido-alliance] The FIDO2 Project is a joint effort between the FIDO Alliance and the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C) whose goal is to create strong authentication for the web.
[src:webauthn-fido2/fido-alliance] At its core, FIDO2 consists of the W3C Web Authentication (WebAuthn) standard and the FIDO Client to Authenticator Protocol 2 (CTAP2).
[src:webauthn-fido2/fido-alliance] FIDO2 is based upon previous work done by the FIDO Alliance, in particular the Universal 2nd Factor (U2F) authentication standard.
[src:webauthn-fido2/fido-alliance] Taken together, WebAuthn and CTAP specify a standard authentication protocol where the protocol endpoints consist of a user-controlled cryptographic authenticator (such as a smartphone or a hardware security key) and a WebAuthn Relying Party (also called a FIDO2 server).
[src:webauthn-fido2/fido-alliance] A web user agent (i.e., a web browser) together with a WebAuthn client form an intermediary between the authenticator and the relying party.
[src:webauthn-fido2/fido-alliance] A single WebAuthn client Device may support multiple WebAuthn clients.
[src:webauthn-fido2/fido-alliance] For example, a laptop may support multiple clients, one for each conforming user agent running on the laptop.
[src:webauthn-fido2/fido-alliance] A conforming user agent implements the WebAuthn JavaScript API.
[src:webauthn-fido2/fido-alliance] As its name implies, the Client to Authenticator Protocol (CTAP) enables a conforming cryptographic authenticator to interoperate with a WebAuthn client.
[src:webauthn-fido2/fido-alliance] The CTAP specification refers to two protocol versions called CTAP1/U2F and CTAP2.
[src:webauthn-fido2/fido-alliance] An authenticator that implements one of these protocols is typically referred to as a U2F authenticator or a FIDO2 authenticator, respectively.
[src:webauthn-fido2/fido-alliance] A FIDO2 authenticator that also implements the CTAP1/U2F protocol is backward compatible with U2F.
[src:webauthn-fido2/fido-alliance] The invention of using a smartphone as a cryptographic authenticator on a computer network is claimed in US patent 7,366,913 filed in 2002.
[src:webauthn-fido2/universal-2nd-factor] While initially developed by Google and Yubico, with contribution from NXP Semiconductors, the standard is now hosted by the FIDO Alliance.
[src:webauthn-fido2/universal-2nd-factor] While time-based one-time password (TOTPs) (e.g.
[src:webauthn-fido2/universal-2nd-factor] 6-digit codes generated on Google Authenticator) were a significant improvement over SMS-based security codes, a number of security vulnerabilities were still possible to exploit, which U2F sought to improve.
[src:webauthn-fido2/universal-2nd-factor] In terms of disadvantages, one significant difference and potential drawback to be considered regarding hardware-based U2F solutions is that unlike with TOTP shared-secret methods, there is no possibility of "backing up" recovery codes or shared secrets.
[src:webauthn-fido2/universal-2nd-factor] If a hardware duplicate or alternative hardware key is not kept and the original U2F hardware key is lost, no recovery of the key is possible (because the private key exists only in hardware).
[src:webauthn-fido2/universal-2nd-factor] Therefore, for services that do not provide any alternative account recovery method, the use of U2F should be carefully considered.
[src:webauthn-fido2/universal-2nd-factor] The USB devices communicate with the host computer using the human interface device (HID) protocol, the same protocol used by mice, keyboards, and other input devices.
[src:webauthn-fido2/universal-2nd-factor] This avoids the need for the user to install special hardware driver software in the host computer and permits application software (such as a browser) to directly access the security features of the device without user effort other than possessing and inserting the device.
[src:webauthn-fido2/universal-2nd-factor] Once communication is established, the application exercises a challenge–response authentication with the device using public-key cryptography methods and a secret unique device key manufactured into the device.
[src:webauthn-fido2/universal-2nd-factor] The device key is vulnerable to malicious manufacturer duplication.
[src:webauthn-fido2/universal-2nd-factor] In 2020, independent security researchers found a method to extract private keys from Google Titan Key, a popular U2F hardware security token.
[src:webauthn-fido2/universal-2nd-factor] The method required physical access to the key for several hours, several thousand euros-worth of equipment, and was destructive to the plastic case of the key.
[src:webauthn-fido2/universal-2nd-factor] The attackers concluded that the difficulty of the attack meant that people were still safer to use the keys than not.
[src:webauthn-fido2/universal-2nd-factor] The attack was possible due to a vulnerability in the A700X microchip made by NXP Semiconductors, which is also used in security tokens made by Feitian and Yubico, meaning that those tokens are also vulnerable.
[src:webauthn-fido2/universal-2nd-factor] The vulnerability was responsibly disclosed to the affected manufacturers so that it might be fixed in future products.
[src:webauthn-fido2/universal-2nd-factor] U2F security keys are supported by Google Chrome since version 38, Firefox since version 57 and Opera since version 40.
[src:webauthn-fido2/universal-2nd-factor] U2F security keys can be used as an additional method of two-step verification on online services that support the U2F protocol, including Google, Azure, Dropbox, GitHub, GitLab, Bitbucket, Nextcloud, Facebook, and others.
[src:webauthn-fido2/universal-2nd-factor] Chrome, Firefox, and Opera were, as of 2015, the only browsers supporting U2F natively.
[src:webauthn-fido2/universal-2nd-factor] Microsoft has enabled FIDO 2.0 support for Windows 10's Windows Hello login platform.
[src:webauthn-fido2/universal-2nd-factor] Microsoft Edge browser gained support for U2F in the October 2018 Windows Update.
[src:webauthn-fido2/universal-2nd-factor] Microsoft accounts, including Office 365, OneDrive, and other Microsoft services, do not yet have U2F support.
[src:webauthn-fido2/universal-2nd-factor] Mozilla has integrated it into Firefox 57, and enabled it by default in Firefox 60 and Thunderbird 60.
[src:webauthn-fido2/universal-2nd-factor] Microsoft Edge starting from build 17723 support FIDO2.
[src:webauthn-fido2/universal-2nd-factor] As of iOS and iPadOS 13.3 Apple now supports U2F in the Safari browser on those platforms.
[src:webauthn-fido2/universal-2nd-factor] Additional specification documents may be obtained from the FIDO web site.
[src:webauthn-fido2/universal-2nd-factor] The U2F 1.0 Proposed Standard (October 9, 2014) was the starting point for a short-lived specification known as the FIDO 2.0 Proposed Standard (September 4, 2015).
[src:webauthn-fido2/universal-2nd-factor] Meanwhile the U2F 1.2 Proposed Standard (April 11, 2017) became the starting point for the Client to Authenticator Protocol (CTAP) Proposed Standard, which was published on September 27, 2017.
[src:webauthn-fido2/universal-2nd-factor] FIDO CTAP complements W3C WebAuthn, both of which are in scope for the FIDO2 Project.
[src:webauthn-fido2/universal-2nd-factor] WebAuthn and CTAP provide a complete replacement for U2F, which has been renamed "CTAP1" in the latest version of the FIDO2 standard.
[src:webauthn-fido2/universal-2nd-factor] The WebAuthn protocol is backward-compatible (via the AppID extension) with U2F-only security keys but the U2F protocol is not compatible with a WebAuthn-only authenticator.
[src:webauthn-fido2/universal-2nd-factor] Some authenticators support both U2F and WebAuthn while some WebAuthn clients support keys created via the legacy U2F API.
[src:webauthn-fido2/webauthn] To use WebAuthn, users require a compatible authenticator.
[src:webauthn-fido2/webauthn] The standard does not specify how to store the keys required for signing, so a variety of authenticator types can be used.
[src:webauthn-fido2/webauthn] The most common authenticator type is a platform authenticator, which is built into the operating system of the device.
[src:webauthn-fido2/webauthn] Common platform authenticators include Android, Apple Keychain and Windows Hello.
[src:webauthn-fido2/webauthn] These make use of hardware security features (such as TEE and TPM), and often sync credentials between devices for ease-of-use.
[src:webauthn-fido2/webauthn] Another common authenticator type is a roaming authenticator, where a separate hardware device authenticates the user by connecting over USB, Bluetooth Low Energy, or near-field communications (NFC).
[src:webauthn-fido2/webauthn] Most smartphones can be used as roaming authenticators, and dedicated physical security keys are also used.
[src:webauthn-fido2/webauthn] WebAuthn is effectively backward compatible with FIDO Universal 2nd Factor (U2F) as they both use the CTAP protocol.
[src:webauthn-fido2/webauthn] Password managers can also be used as an authenticator, often with cloud sync.
[src:webauthn-fido2/webauthn] Where credentials sync is not viable or possible, WebAuthn Hybrid Transport can be used to access credentials stored on another authenticator such as a smartphone.
[src:webauthn-fido2/webauthn] Like legacy U2F, WebAuthn is resistant to some phishing attacks as the authenticator only offers credentials that were registered on the same website.
[src:webauthn-fido2/webauthn] However, unlike U2F, WebAuthn can be implemented in a passwordless manner.
[src:webauthn-fido2/webauthn] Moreover, a roaming hardware authenticator resists malware, since the keys are stored on a separate device, which prevents the malware from accessing them directly.
[src:webauthn-fido2/webauthn] The WebAuthn Level 1 and 2 standards were published as W3C Recommendations on 4 March 2019 and 8 April 2021 respectively.
[src:webauthn-fido2/webauthn] A Level 3 specification is currently a *First Public Working Draft* (FPWD).
[src:webauthn-fido2/webauthn] WebAuthn is a core component of the FIDO2 Project under the guidance of the FIDO Alliance.
[src:webauthn-fido2/webauthn] FIDO2 is the successor to FIDO Universal 2nd Factor (U2F).
[src:webauthn-fido2/webauthn] Whereas U2F only supports multi-factor mode, having been designed to strengthen existing username/password-based login flows, FIDO2 adds support for single-factor mode.
[src:webauthn-fido2/webauthn] In multi-factor mode, the authenticator is activated by a test of *user presence*, which usually consists of a simple button push; no password is required.
[src:webauthn-fido2/webauthn] In single-factor mode, the authenticator (*something you have*) performs *user verification*.
[src:webauthn-fido2/webauthn] Regardless of mode, the authenticator never shares its secrets or biometric data with the website.
[src:webauthn-fido2/webauthn] Moreover, a single user's secret or biometric works with all websites, as the authenticator selects the correct cryptographic key material to use for the service requesting authentication after user verification was completed successfully.
[src:webauthn-fido2/webauthn] A secret and biometric on the authenticator can be used together, similarly to how they would be used on a smartphone.
[src:webauthn-fido2/webauthn] For example, a fingerprint provides convenient access to user's smartphone, but occasionally fingerprint access fails, in which case user can use a PIN.
[src:webauthn-fido2/webauthn] When Apple first introduced passkeys to the public in 2022, they emphasized their first-party platform integrations.
[src:webauthn-fido2/webauthn] This, combined with the lack of clear communication from other industry leaders, led some to speculate that passkeys were proprietary to Apple, which was not the case.
[src:webauthn-fido2/webauthn] As browsers and websites began to implement WebAuthn, the inconsistent feature-sets resulted in a variety of understandings of what exactly counted as a passkey.
[src:webauthn-fido2/webauthn] Some people assumed that a passkey required management by a platform authenticator, or needed synchronization using the cloud.
[src:webauthn-fido2/webauthn] A better definition is that a passkey is any WebAuthn credential managed by any WebAuthn authenticator.
[src:webauthn-fido2/webauthn] This definition covers most of what different vendors refer to and accept as *passkeys*.
[src:webauthn-fido2/webauthn] WebAuthn specifies how a claimant demonstrates possession and control of a FIDO2 authenticator to a verifier called the WebAuthn Relying Party.
[src:webauthn-fido2/webauthn] The authentication process is mediated by an entity called the WebAuthn Client, which is little more than a conforming web browser.
[src:webauthn-fido2/webauthn] Authenticator is a multi-factor cryptographic authenticator that uses public-key cryptography to sign an authentication assertion targeted at the WebAuthn Relying Party.
[src:webauthn-fido2/webauthn] Assuming the authenticator uses either a facial recognition, fingerprint or PIN for user verification, the authenticator itself is *something you have* while the facial recognition and fingerprint (biometric) are *something you are* and the PIN is *something you know*.
[src:webauthn-fido2/webauthn] To initiate the WebAuthn authentication flow, the WebAuthn Relying Party indicates its intentions to the WebAuthn Client (i.e., the browser) via JavaScript.
[src:webauthn-fido2/webauthn] The WebAuthn Client communicates with the authenticator using a JavaScript API implemented in the browser.
[src:webauthn-fido2/webauthn] A roaming authenticator conforms to the FIDO Client to Authenticator Protocol (CTAP), and connected over USB, Bluetooth Low Energy, or near-field communications (NFC).
[src:webauthn-fido2/webauthn] WebAuthn does not strictly require a roaming hardware authenticator.
[src:webauthn-fido2/webauthn] Alternatively, a software authenticator (e.g., implemented on a smartphone) or a platform authenticator (i.e., an authenticator implemented directly on the WebAuthn Client Device) may be used.
[src:webauthn-fido2/webauthn] Relevant examples of platform authenticators include Windows Hello and the Android operating system.
[src:webauthn-fido2/webauthn] WebAuthn Hybrid Transport allows the WebAuthn Client to access credentials stored on another authenticator such as a smartphone, useful in certain situations where credential sync is not viable.
[src:webauthn-fido2/webauthn] There is a lingering misunderstanding among users that biometric data is transmitted over the network in the same manner as passwords, which is not the case.
[src:webauthn-fido2/webauthn] When the WebAuthn Relying Party receives the signed authentication assertion from the browser, the digital signature on the assertion is verified using a trusted public key for the user.
[src:webauthn-fido2/webauthn] To obtain a public key for the user, the WebAuthn Relying Party initiates a WebAuthn registration flow that is similar to the authentication flow illustrated above.
[src:webauthn-fido2/webauthn] The primary difference is that the authenticator now signs an attestation statement with its attestation private key.
[src:webauthn-fido2/webauthn] The signed attestation statement contains a copy of the public key that the WebAuthn Relying Party ultimately uses to verify a signed authentication assertion.
[src:webauthn-fido2/webauthn] The attestation certificate contains metadata describing the authenticator itself.
[src:webauthn-fido2/webauthn] The digital signature on the attestation statement is verified with the trusted attestation public key for that particular model of authenticator.
[src:webauthn-fido2/webauthn] How the WebAuthn Relying Party obtains its store of trusted attestation public keys is unspecified.
[src:webauthn-fido2/webauthn] One option is to use the FIDO metadata service.
[src:webauthn-fido2/webauthn] The attestation type specified in the JavaScript determines the trust model.
[src:webauthn-fido2/webauthn] For instance, an attestation type called self-attestation may be desired, for which the trust model is essentially trust on first use.
[src:webauthn-fido2/webauthn] The WebAuthn Level 1 standard was published as a W3C Recommendation by the Web Authentication Working Group on 4 March 2019.
[src:webauthn-fido2/webauthn] WebAuthn is supported by Google Chrome, Mozilla Firefox, Microsoft Edge, Apple Safari and Opera.
[src:webauthn-fido2/webauthn] The desktop version of Google Chrome has supported WebAuthn since version 67.
[src:webauthn-fido2/webauthn] Firefox, which had not fully supported the previous FIDO U2F standard, included and enabled WebAuthn in Firefox version 60, released on 9 May 2018.
[src:webauthn-fido2/webauthn] An early Windows Insider release of Microsoft Edge (Build 17682) implemented a version of WebAuthn that works with both Windows Hello as well as external security keys.
[src:webauthn-fido2/webauthn] Existing FIDO U2F security keys are largely compatible with the WebAuthn standard, though WebAuthn added the ability to reference a unique per-account "user handle" identifier, which older authenticators are unable to store.
[src:webauthn-fido2/webauthn] One of the first FIDO2-compatible authenticators was the second-generation Security Key by Yubico, announced on 10 April 2018.
[src:webauthn-fido2/webauthn] The first FIDO2-compatible authenticators with a display was Trezor Model T by SatoshiLabs, announced on 6 November 2019.
[src:webauthn-fido2/webauthn] Trezor Model T was also the first authenticator that allowed users to select which FIDO2 resident credential should be used directly on a device.
[src:webauthn-fido2/webauthn] The first Security Level 2 certified FIDO2 key, called "Goldengate" was announced one year later by eWBM on 8 April 2019.
[src:webauthn-fido2/webauthn] Dropbox announced support for WebAuthn logins (as a 2nd factor) on 8 May 2018.
[src:webauthn-fido2/webauthn] Apple announced that Face ID or Touch ID could be used as a WebAuthn platform authenticator with Safari on 24 June 2020.
[src:webauthn-fido2/webauthn] Several password managers such as Bitwarden and Dashlane support WebAuthn.
[src:webauthn-fido2/webauthn] WebAuthn implements an extension of the W3C's more general Credential Management API, which is an attempt to formalize the interaction between websites and web browsers when exchanging user credentials.
[src:webauthn-fido2/webauthn] The Web Authentication API extends the Credential Management `navigator.credentials.create()` and `navigator.credentials.get()` JavaScript methods so they accept a `publicKey` parameter.
[src:webauthn-fido2/webauthn] To check if a browser supports WebAuthn, scripts should check if the `window.PublicKeyCredential` interface is defined.
[src:webauthn-fido2/webauthn] In addition to `PublicKeyCredential`, the standard also defines the `AuthenticatorResponse`, `AuthenticatorAttestationResponse`, and `AuthenticatorAssertionResponse` interfaces in addition to a variety of dictionaries and other datatypes.
[src:webauthn-fido2/webauthn] The API does not allow direct access to or manipulation of private keys, beyond requesting their initial creation.
[src:webauthn-fido2/webauthn] In August 2018, Paragon Initiative Enterprises conducted a security audit of the WebAuthn standard.
[src:webauthn-fido2/webauthn] While they could not find any specific exploits, they revealed some serious weaknesses in the way the underlying cryptography is used and mandated by the standard.
[src:webauthn-fido2/webauthn] Paragon Initiative Enterprises also criticized how the standard was initially developed, as the proposal was not made public in advance and experienced cryptographers were not asked for suggestions and feedback.
[src:webauthn-fido2/webauthn] Hence the standard was not subject to broad cryptographic research from the academic world.
[src:webauthn-fido2/webauthn] Despite these shortcomings, Paragon Initiative Enterprises still encourage users to continue to use WebAuthn but have come up with some recommendations for potential implementers and developers of the standard that they hope can be implemented before the standard is finalized.
[src:webauthn-fido2/webauthn] Avoiding such mistakes as early as possible would protect the industry from any challenges that are introduced by broken standards and the need for backwards compatibility.
[src:webauthn-fido2/webauthn] ECDAA was only designed to use in combination with device attestation.
[src:webauthn-fido2/webauthn] This particular feature of WebAuthn is not necessarily required for authentication to work.
[src:webauthn-fido2/webauthn] Current implementations allow the user to decide whether an attestation statement is sent during the registration ceremony.
[src:webauthn-fido2/webauthn] Independently, relying parties can choose to require attestation or not.
[src:webauthn-fido2/webauthn] ECDAA was removed from WebAuthn Level 2 as it was not implemented by browsers nor relying parties.
[src:webauthn-fido2/yubikey] The **YubiKey** is a collection of hardware authentication devices manufactured by **Yubico** AB (Nasdaq Stockholm: YUBICO), a company founded in 2007 by Jakob and Stina Ehrensvärd and headquartered in Stockholm, Sweden, with an American subdivision incorporated in Santa Clara, California.
[src:webauthn-fido2/yubikey] As of March 2026, the YubiKey range includes a number of devices that support the FIDO2 authentication standard and come in various sizes and interface formats.
[src:webauthn-fido2/yubikey] The flagship YubiKey 5 Series also supports a number of other industry standards including OATH, PIV and OpenPGP, as well as a legacy proprietary "OTP" applet with various functions.
[src:webauthn-fido2/yubikey] Yubico also offers a hardware security module, the YubiHSM 2.
[src:webauthn-fido2/yubikey] The YubiKey 5 Series and YubiHSM 2 have FIPS 140-2–certified versions for government or enterprise clients subject to regulatory requirements.
[src:webauthn-fido2/yubikey] YubiKeys can be used to authenticate access to websites, apps, operating systems, remote servers, networks and other environments, with some YubiKey products also supporting encryption/decryption (of files or messages) and digital signing.
[src:webauthn-fido2/yubikey] The name "YubiKey" derives from the phrase "your ubiquitous key" and "yubi", the Japanese word for finger, emphasising the YubiKey's versatility and the physical touch used to verify the user's presence.
[src:webauthn-fido2/yubikey] Yubico was founded in 2007 and began offering a Pilot Box for developers in November of that year.
[src:webauthn-fido2/yubikey] The original YubiKey product was shown at the annual RSA Conference in April 2008, and a more robust YubiKey 2.0 model was launched in 2009.
[src:webauthn-fido2/yubikey] The YubiKey 2.0 added dual "slots", for storing two distinct configurations with separate AES secrets and other settings.
[src:webauthn-fido2/yubikey] When authenticating, the first slot is used by only briefly pressing the button on the device, while the second slot is used by holding the button for 2 to 5 seconds.
[src:webauthn-fido2/yubikey] In 2010, Yubico began offering the YubiKey OATH and YubiKey RFID models.
[src:webauthn-fido2/yubikey] The YubiKey OATH added the ability to generate 6- and 8-character OATH passwords in addition to the 32-character passwords used by Yubico's own OTP scheme.
[src:webauthn-fido2/yubikey] The YubiKey RFID model included the OATH capability plus also included a MIFARE Classic 1k radio-frequency identification chip, though that was a separate device within the package that could not be configured with the normal Yubico software over a USB connection.
[src:webauthn-fido2/yubikey] Yubico announced the YubiKey Nano in February 2012, a miniaturized version of the standard YubiKey which was designed so it would fit almost entirely inside a USB port and only expose a small touch pad for the button.
[src:webauthn-fido2/yubikey] Most later models of the YubiKey have also been available in both standard and "nano" sizes.
[src:webauthn-fido2/yubikey] 2012 also saw the introduction of the YubiKey Neo, which improved upon the previous YubiKey RFID product by integrating near-field communication (NFC).
[src:webauthn-fido2/yubikey] The YubiKey Neo (and Neo-n, a "nano" version of the device) was able to transmit one-time passwords to NFC readers as part of a configurable URL contained in a NFC message.
[src:webauthn-fido2/yubikey] The Neo was also able to communicate using the CCID smart-card protocol in addition to USB HID (human interface device) keyboard emulation.
[src:webauthn-fido2/yubikey] The CCID mode is used for PIV smart card and OpenPGP support, while USB HID is used for the one-time password authentication schemes.
[src:webauthn-fido2/yubikey] In 2014, the YubiKey Neo was updated with FIDO Universal 2nd Factor (U2F) support.
[src:webauthn-fido2/yubikey] Yubico, Google and NXP Semiconductors co-developed the FIDO U2F standard.
[src:webauthn-fido2/yubikey] Later that year, Yubico released the "FIDO U2F Security Key", which specifically included U2F support but none of the other one-time password, static password, smart card, or NFC features of previous YubiKeys.
[src:webauthn-fido2/yubikey] At launch, it was correspondingly sold at a lower price point of just $18, compared to $25 for the YubiKey Standard ($40 for the Nano version) and $50 for the YubiKey Neo ($60 for Neo-n).
[src:webauthn-fido2/yubikey] Some of the pre-release devices issued by Google during FIDO/U2F development reported themselves as "Yubico WinUSB Gnubby (gnubby1)".
[src:webauthn-fido2/yubikey] In April 2015, the company launched the YubiKey Edge in both standard and nano form factors.
[src:webauthn-fido2/yubikey] This slotted in between the Neo and FIDO U2F products feature-wise, as it was designed to handle OTP and U2F authentication, but did not include smart card or NFC support.
[src:webauthn-fido2/yubikey] The YubiKey 4 family of devices was first launched in November 2015, with USB-A models in both standard and nano sizes.
[src:webauthn-fido2/yubikey] The YubiKey 4 includes most features of the YubiKey Neo, including increasing the allowed OpenPGP key size to 4096 bits (vs. the previous 2048), but dropped the NFC capability of the Neo.
[src:webauthn-fido2/yubikey] At CES 2017, Yubico announced an expansion of the YubiKey 4 series to support a new USB-C design.
[src:webauthn-fido2/yubikey] The YubiKey 4C was released on February 13, 2017.
[src:webauthn-fido2/yubikey] On Android OS over the USB-C connection, only the one-time password feature is supported by the Android OS and YubiKey, with other features not currently supported including Universal 2nd Factor (U2F).
[src:webauthn-fido2/yubikey] A 4C Nano version became available in September 2017.
[src:webauthn-fido2/yubikey] The device was only available in the "standard" form factor with a USB-A connector.
[src:webauthn-fido2/yubikey] Like the previous FIDO U2F Security Key, it used a key icon on its touch sensor.
[src:webauthn-fido2/yubikey] At launch, it was blue in color like the previous FIDO U2F Security Key and distinguished by a number "2" etched into the plastic between the touch sensor and the keyring hole.
[src:webauthn-fido2/yubikey] It was also less expensive than the YubiKey Neo and YubiKey 4 models, costing $20 per unit at launch because it lacked the OTP and smart card features of those previous devices, though it retained FIDO U2F capability.
[src:webauthn-fido2/yubikey] The non-NFC versions were also retired, and the "NFC" part of the Security Key NFC name became less prominent.
[src:webauthn-fido2/yubikey] It achieves this by hosting multiple "applets" with memory slots/addresses on its secure, tamper-resistant hardware, with most applets being based on a widespread, cross-platform industry standard.
[src:webauthn-fido2/yubikey] The applets and their protocols are understood by and can be interacted with using a wide variety of software, ranging from Yubico applications to third-party software, web browsers and operating systems, although some administrative tasks can only be performed by Yubico tools.
[src:webauthn-fido2/yubikey] The FIDO2 (sometimes referred to as FIDO2/WebAuthn, WebAuthn being the browser/OS implementation standard) applet can store passkeys for passwordless authentication via the CTAP2 protocol or two-factor authentication (2FA) via the CTAP1 (formerly U2F) protocol.
[src:webauthn-fido2/yubikey] The OATH applet can store seeds for time-based one-time passwords (TOTP) or HMAC-based one-time passwords (HOTP).
[src:webauthn-fido2/yubikey] The YubiKey 5 Series also has a PIV (a smart card standard) applet and an OpenPGP applet, which each have widespread applications from authentication to message and file encryption and signing.
[src:webauthn-fido2/yubikey] This applet causes the YubiKey to function as a USB HID (similar to a keyboard) to enter the "OTP" slot contents on short press (slot 1) or long press (slot 2) of the YubiKey's touch sensor (unless challenge–response is used in the given slot).
[src:webauthn-fido2/yubikey] This USB HID functionality does not apply to the other applets.
[src:webauthn-fido2/yubikey] A "Yubico OTP" is factory-programmed into slot 1 of the YubiKey 5; the user can regenerate it or overwrite the slot for a different use, but any user-generated Yubico OTPs will have a different prefix ("vv" instead of "cc").
[src:webauthn-fido2/yubikey] The product lineup as of March 2026 also includes the following products.
[src:webauthn-fido2/yubikey] The YubiKey Security Key Series is a cheaper, "streamlined" offering that only contains the FIDO2 applet, does not contain a serial number (to thwart tracking) and does not have a nano or non-NFC version.
[src:webauthn-fido2/yubikey] The YubiKey Bio Series is another offering that supports biometric authentication through its fingerprint sensor.
[src:webauthn-fido2/yubikey] This series does not have a nano or NFC version.
[src:webauthn-fido2/yubikey] The standard YubiKey Bio Series (known as the "FIDO Edition") only supports FIDO2, but in 2024, Yubico announced a "Multi-protocol Edition" that also supports PIV, available to enterprise clients on the YubiEnterprise Subscription.
[src:webauthn-fido2/yubikey] Yubico also offers the YubiHSM 2, a hardware security module for generating and storing master cryptographic keys for servers.
[src:webauthn-fido2/yubikey] Yubico offers a FIPS 140-2–certified version of the YubiKey 5 Series for government and enterprise clients subject to regulation requiring stringent certification.
[src:webauthn-fido2/yubikey] In November 2024, Yubico announced that the YubiKey 5 FIPS Series was undergoing certification according to the new FIPS 140-3 standard.
[src:webauthn-fido2/yubikey] The YubiHSM 2 also has a FIPS 140-2–certified version.
[src:webauthn-fido2/yubikey] Yubico had previously offered CSPN-certified versions of the YubiKey 5 Series for European markets (CSPN is an ANSSI certification), but these were discontinued in 2024 due to limited demand.
[src:webauthn-fido2/yubikey] A list of the primary features and capabilities of the YubiKey products.
[src:webauthn-fido2/yubikey] When being used for one-time passwords and stored static passwords, the YubiKey emits characters using a modified hexadecimal alphabet which is intended to be as independent of system keyboard settings as possible.
[src:webauthn-fido2/yubikey] This alphabet, invented by Yubico specifically for this application, is referred to as Modhex (sometimes written "ModHex" or "modhex") and consists of the characters "cbdefghijklnrtuv", corresponding to the hexadecimal digits "0123456789abcdef".
[src:webauthn-fido2/yubikey] Since YubiKeys use raw keyboard scan codes in USB HID mode, there can be problems when using the devices on computers that are set up with different keyboard layouts, such as Dvorak.
[src:webauthn-fido2/yubikey] Modhex was created to avoid conflicts between different keyboard layouts.
[src:webauthn-fido2/yubikey] It only uses characters that are located in the same place on most Latin alphabet keyboards, but is still 16 characters, allowing it to be used in place of hexadecimal.
[src:webauthn-fido2/yubikey] Alternatively, this issue can be addressed by using operating system features to temporarily switch to a standard US keyboard layout (or similar) when using one-time passwords.
[src:webauthn-fido2/yubikey] However, YubiKey Neo and later devices can be configured with alternate scan codes to match layouts that aren't compatible with the Modhex character set.
[src:webauthn-fido2/yubikey] This problem only applies to YubiKey products in HID mode, where it must emulate keyboard input.
[src:webauthn-fido2/yubikey] U2F authentication in YubiKey products bypasses this problem by using the alternate U2FHID protocol, which sends and receives raw binary messages instead of keyboard scan codes.
[src:webauthn-fido2/yubikey] CCID mode acts as a smart card reader, which does not use HID protocols at all.
[src:webauthn-fido2/yubikey] Most of the code that runs on a YubiKey is closed-source.
[src:webauthn-fido2/yubikey] While Yubico has released some code for industry standard functionality like OpenPGP and HOTP, it was disclosed that as of the 4th generation of the product this is not the same code that the new units ship with.
[src:webauthn-fido2/yubikey] Because new units are permanently firmware-locked at the factory, it is not possible to compile the open-source code and load it on the device manually; a user must trust that the code on a new key is authentic and secure.
[src:webauthn-fido2/yubikey] Code for other functionality such as U2F, PIV and Modhex is entirely closed source.
[src:webauthn-fido2/yubikey] In October 2017, security researchers found a vulnerability (known as ROCA) in the implementation of RSA keypair generation in a cryptographic library used by a large number of Infineon security chips, as used in a wide range of security keys and security token products (including YubiKey).
[src:webauthn-fido2/yubikey] The vulnerability allows an attacker to reconstruct the private key by using the public key.
[src:webauthn-fido2/yubikey] All YubiKey 4, YubiKey 4C, and YubiKey 4 Nano devices within the revisions 4.2.6 to 4.3.4 were affected by this vulnerability.
[src:webauthn-fido2/yubikey] Yubico remedied this issue in all shipping YubiKey 4 devices by switching to a different key generation function and offered free replacements for any affected keys until March 31, 2019.
[src:webauthn-fido2/yubikey] In some cases, the issue could be bypassed by generating new keys outside of the YubiKey and importing them onto the device.
[src:webauthn-fido2/yubikey] In January 2018, Yubico disclosed a moderate vulnerability where password protection for the OTP functionality on the YubiKey NEO could be bypassed under certain conditions.
[src:webauthn-fido2/yubikey] The issue was corrected as of firmware version 3.5.0, and Yubico offered free replacement keys to any user claiming to be affected until April 1, 2019.
[src:webauthn-fido2/yubikey] In June 2019, Yubico released a security advisory reporting reduced randomness in FIPS-certified devices with firmware version 4.4.2 and 4.4.4 (there is no version 4.4.3), shortly after power-up.
[src:webauthn-fido2/yubikey] Security keys with reduced randomness may leave keys more easily discovered and compromised than expected.
[src:webauthn-fido2/yubikey] The issue affected the FIPS series only, and then only certain scenarios, although FIPS ECDSA usage was "at higher risk".
[src:webauthn-fido2/yubikey] The company offered free replacements for any affected keys.
[src:webauthn-fido2/yubikey] In September 2024, security researchers from NinjaLab discovered a cryptographic flaw in Infineon chips that would allow a person to clone a YubiKey if an attacker gained physical access to it.
[src:webauthn-fido2/yubikey] The security vulnerability permanently affects all YubiKeys prior to firmware update 5.7.
[src:webauthn-fido2/yubikey] Yubico rated the issue as "moderate", citing the need for an attacker to have physical access to the key, expensive equipment, and advanced cryptographic and technical knowledge.
[src:webauthn-fido2/yubikey] In 2018, Yubico gave away free YubiKeys with laser-engraved logos to new *WIRED* and *Ars Technica* subscribers.
[src:webauthn-fido2/yubikey] Yubico provided 500 YubiKeys to protesters during the 2019–2020 Hong Kong protests.
[src:webauthn-fido2/yubikey] The company stated that the decision was based on their mission to protect vulnerable Internet users and work with free speech supporters.
